  <li id="comment-42397" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Marie Z.</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2014/10/the-satisfaction/#comment-42397"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-10-12T02:19:50-04:00">Sunday, October 12, 2014 at 2:19 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>THERE IS A WAY TO MAKE THIS SANS SUGAR!<br />German Pflaumenmuss (taught to me by Oma (grandma))</p>
<p>5.25 lbs. Italian plums (or Damsons)&#8211; weighed before pits removed<br />8 whole cloves<br />1 cinnamon stick<br />1 vanilla bean</p>
<p>Wipe (polish) each plum and cut into small pieces (removing the pit as you go) and place them in a heavy pot (I use a 16 qt. or 12 qt. stock pot.) and add 1/2 cup of water. Bring the plums to a boil, stirring often enough so that they don&#39;t burn on the bottom.<br />Make a spice bag: tie up the cloves, cinnamon stick and vanilla bean in a double thickness piece of cheesecloth. Place it in the pot. Turn the heat down and boil the plums gently (lightly bubbling) for 2.5 to 3 hours, stirring every 10 to 15 minutes.  The jam should be very thick. <br />Ladle the jam into quart-size freezer bags (one rounded cup per bag). Press the bags flat and freeze them flat on a cookie sheet.</p>
    </div>

