    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Aren&#8217;t Italian plums delightful? The home we are staying in has a couple of old trees in the yard. We had our best year yet for plums and harvested thirty-six pounds.  After eating a bunch (of course!), we ended up making jam, chutney, barbecue sauce and spiced pickled plums. The jam is wonderful (the color!), but I&#8217;m especially pleased with that last one. </p>
<p>We also have a quince tree and make Paradise Jelly, an old American traditional of quince, apples and cranberries, with a flavor all its own. We&#8217;ve made it three times now and each time it&#8217;s a different, rich shade of pink. The tree only produces a good crop alternating years, unfortunately.</p>
